ERP EXPERIMENT: EEG SIGNAL (HYPOTHESES 4-6)

1. HYPOTHESES

Hypothesis 4

Brain responses (N400, P600) to well-formed sentences will differ between native-accented and foreign-accented speech (“grammatical tinnitus”).

Hypothesis 5

Sentences with grammatical errors will elicit reduced brain responses (N400, P600) in foreign-accented speech in comparison to native-accented speech.

Hypothesis 6

Sentences with phonetic errors will elicit reduced brain responses (PMN, N400, P600) in foreign-accented speech in comparison to native-accented speech.

2. VARIABLES

SENTENCE_TYPE The type of manipulation applied to the sentence. Values: well-formed/grammatical/phonetic.

SENTENCE_ACCENT Accent of the speaker producing the presented sentence.

ERP_MEAN_AMPLITUDE Mean of all voltages recorded at the given channel in the specified time-window.

ERP_RESPONSE_GRAM Response accuracy to the grammaticality question. Values: correct, incorrect.

ERP_ROI Region of interest. A group of channels representing major scalp areas.

Current ROI values:

  • frontal {‘F3’, ‘Fz’, ‘F4’ }
  • central {‘C3’, ‘Cz’, ‘C4’}
  • parietal {‘P3’, ‘Pz’, ‘P4’}

6. CONCLUSIONS

Hypothesis 4

Brain responses (N400, P600) to well-formed sentences will differ between native-accented and foreign-accented speech (“grammatical tinnitus”).

300-500 ms The hypothesis was not confirmed.

500-900 ms The hypothesis was not confirmed.

Hypothesis 5

Sentences with grammatical errors will elicit reduced brain responses (N400, P600) in foreign-accented speech in comparison to native-accented speech.

300-500 ms The hypothesis was not confirmed.

500-900 ms The hypothesis was not confirmed.

Hypothesis 6

Sentences with phonetic errors will elicit reduced brain responses (PMN, N400, P600) in foreign-accented speech in comparison to native-accented speech.

300-500 ms The hypothesis was not confirmed.

500-900 ms The hypothesis was not confirmed.
